{"cursor":"8526","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":":This is about the Roman general and consul; for other Romans of that name, see\n[[Marcus Atilius Regulus (disambiguation)]]. {{Infobox Politician\n| name = Marcus Atilius Regulus image = Lens, Cornelis - Regulus Returning to\n| Carthage - 1791.jpg caption = Regulus returning to [[Carthage]] (1791) by\n| Cornelis Cels birth_date = Before 307 BC birth_place = Roman Republic\n| residence = death_date = 250 BC death_place = Carthage office = Consul of the\n| Roman Republic term_start = 267 BC term_end = 267 BC predecessor = Publius\n| Sempronius Sophus and Appius Claudius Russus successor = Decimus Iunius Pera\n| and Numerius Fabius Pictor office2 = Consul of the Roman Republic term_start2\n| = 256 BC term_end2 = 256 BC predecessor2 =Lucius Manlius Vulso Longus and\n| Quintus Caedicius successor2 = Marcus Aemilius Paullus and Servius Fulvius\n| Paetinus Nobilior constituency = party = religion = Ancient Roman religion\n| occupation = majority = spouse = children = website = footnotes = nickname =\n| allegiance = Roman Republic branch = serviceyears = rank =General commands =\n| battles ='[[First Punic War]]' Battle of Cape Ecnomus Siege of\n| Aspis Battle of Adys Battle of Tunis\n}} 'Marcus Atilius Regulus' (born probably before 307 BC - 250 BC) was a Roman\nstatesman and general who was consul of the Roman Republic in 267 BC and 256\nBC.\n\nRegulus first became consul in 267 BC, where fought the Messapians. Elected\nconsul again in 256 BC, he served as a general in the First Punic War (256 BC),\nwhere he defeated the Carthaginians in a naval battle at Cape Ecnomus near\nSicily and invaded North Africa, winning victories at Aspis and Adys, until he\nwas defeated and captured at Tunis in 255 BC. After he was released on parole to\nnegotiate a peace, he is supposed to have urged the Roman Senate to refuse the\nproposals and then, over the protests of his own people, to have fulfilled the\nterms of his parole by returning to Carthage, where he according to Roman\ntradition was tortured to death. He was posthumously seen by the Romans as a\nmodel of civic virtue.\n","linknr":221,"url":"Marcus_Atilius_Regulus","recorded":1375083652,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Marcus_Atilius_Regulus&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Marcus_Atilius_Regulus&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Marcus_Atilius_Regulus_(disambiguation)","/wiki/File:Lens,_Cornelis_-_Regulus_Returning_to_Carthage_-_1791.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/Lens%2C_Cornelis_-_Regulus_Returning_to_Carthage_-_1791.jpg/220px-Lens%2C_Cornelis_-_Regulus_Returning_to_Carthage_-_1791.jpg","/wiki/Carthage","/wiki/Cornelis_Cels","/wiki/List_of_Roman_Republican_consuls","/wiki/Roman_Republic","/w/index.php?title=Publius_Sempronius_Sophus&action=edit&redlink=1","/w/index.php?title=Appius_Claudius_Russus&action=edit&redlink=1","/w/index.php?title=Decimus_Iunius_Pera&action=edit&redlink=1","/w/index.php?title=Numerius_Fabius_Pictor&action=edit&redlink=1","/wiki/List_of_Roman_Republican_consuls","/wiki/Roman_Republic","/wiki/Lucius_Manlius_Vulso_Longus","/w/index.php?title=Quintus_Caedicius&action=edit&redlink=1","/w/index.php?ti